}}

''inCider'' in 1986 rated ''Ogre'' with three stars out of four.<ref name="murphy198612">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/inCider_86-12#page/n175/mode/2up | title=Game Room | work=inCider | date=December 1986 | access-date=4 February 2015 | author=Murphy, Brian J. | pages=169–170}}</ref> ''[[Info (magazine)|Info]]'' gave the Commodore 64 version three-plus stars out of five, stating that "the real fun is you against the computer" despite the "limited" graphics and sound. The magazine approved of the user interface, and recommended the "very nice" game to those new to battle simulations.<ref name="info198701">{{Cite magazine |last1=Dunnington |first1=Benn |last2=Brown |first2=Mark R. |last3=Malcolm |first3=Tom |date=January–February 1987 |title=64/128 Gallery |url=https://archive.org/stream/info-magazine-13/Info_Issue_13_1987_Jan-Feb#page/n13/mode/2up |magazine=Info |pages=14–21}}</ref> M. Evan Brooks reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that "even though ''Ogre'' is a faithful adaptation of its parent boardgame, has adequate graphics, and can be fun, it isn't the bargain [...] that the boardgame was".<ref name="CGW36">{{cite magazine |last=Brooks |first=M. Evan  |title=Ogre |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=April 1987 |volume=1 |issue=36 |pages=46–47}}</ref>

''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' rated ''Ogre'' three stars out of five in a 1992 survey of science fiction games<ref name="brooks199211">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1992&pub=2&id=100 | title=Strategy & Wargames: The Future (2000-....) | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=1992–2011 | access-date=4 July 2014 | author=Brooks, M. Evan | pages=99}}</ref> and two-plus stars in a 1994 survey,<ref name="brooks199405">{{Cite magazine
 |last=Brooks
 |first=M. Evan
 |date=May 1994
 |title=Never Trust A Gazfluvian Flingschnogger!
 |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=118 
 |magazine=Computer Gaming World
 |pages=42–58}}</ref> and ranked it #130 in the magazine's 1996 list of ''150 Best Games of All Time''.<ref name="computergamingworld">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | title=150 Best Games of All Time | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1996 | access-date=25 March 2016 | pages=64–80}}</ref>

Tim Robinson reviewed ''Ogre'' in ''[[The Space Gamer|Space Gamer/Fantasy Gamer]]'' No. 81.<ref name="SG">{{cite journal|last=Robinson |first=Tim |date=1987|title=Ogre|journal=[[The Space Gamer|Space Gamer/Fantasy Gamer]]|publisher=[[Diverse Talents, Incorporated]]|issue=81|pages=43}}</ref> Robinson commented that "This is a great game, well worth buying and playing extensively. The computer Ogre is great competition and there are options to play against a human opponent. I can highly recommend this game."<ref name="SG"/>

